					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7060165#post-3920746</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7060165/scp-4222#post-3920746</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 21 Aug 2018 19:35:05 +0000</pubDate>
								<wikidot:authorUserId>3927912</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>This is great! I love the series of non sequiturs and how casually the absurdity is documented. The economic angles are a welcome creative approach to containment and its consequences.</p> <div class="collapsible-block"> <div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none"> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-content"> <p>This little detail</p> <blockquote> <p>~~&quot;Capital isn't scarce; vision is&quot; - Sam Walton~~</p> </blockquote> <p>this observation</p> <blockquote> <p>Typing and easy listening jazz can be heard.</p> </blockquote> <p>and this visual</p> <blockquote> <p>Stomach wall contracts on the left of the frame as gas bubbles shift in the digestive acid. Cheering and excited vocalization by a group of about 15 voices can be heard in the distance.</p> </blockquote> <p>and an all-dolphin MTF are highlights for me.<br /> <br /> <br /> My only note for correction would be a fine, split hair over the anatomy presented:</p> <blockquote> <p>19-278 seconds: Camera rests against sphincter leading into large intestine&#8230;<br /> 279 seconds: Camera passes through duodenum into large intestine.</p> </blockquote> <p>The duodenum is the very first part of the small intestine that connects with the stomach. The most distal segment of the small intestines is called the ileum and is what connects with the large intestine.</p> </div> </div> </div> <p>Will read again.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
